# create a route for each worker node that maps the node's Pod CIDR range to the node's internal IP address.

hypothetical
-------  ------------  --------------
node     internal IP   pod CIDR range
-------  ------------  --------------
worker1  192.168.0.47  10.200.1.0/24
worker2  192.168.0.48  10.200.2.0/24
worker3  192.168.0.49  10.200.3.0/24


 +---------------+  +---------------+  +---------------+
 | worker 1 pod  |  | worker 2 pod  |  | worker 3 pod  |
 | 10.200.1.0/24 |  | 10.200.2.0/24 |  | 10.200.3.0/24 |
 +---------------+  +---------------+  +---------------+
         |                  |                  |
      route to           route to           route to
         |                  |                  |
         V                  V                  V
 +---------------+  +---------------+  +---------------+
 | worker 1 node |  | worker 2 node |  | worker 3 node |
 | 192.168.0.47  |  | 192.168.0.48  |  | 192.168.0.49  |
 +---------------+  +---------------+  +---------------+


So the routing tables on the VMs would have to look like so:

from this node  to reach this cidr  route to this node
--------------  ------------------  ------------------
worker1         10.200.2.0/24       192.168.0.48
worker1         10.200.3.0/24       192.168.0.49
worker2         10.200.1.0/24       192.168.0.47
worker2         10.200.3.0/24       192.168.0.49
worker3         10.200.1.0/24       192.168.0.47
worker3         10.200.2.0/24       192.168.0.48
